facilities.name: BC Centre for Elder Advocacy and Support
Disability Alliance BC - The Advocacy Access Program
UBC Learning Exchange
facilities.description: The Learning Exchange is a place of mind for thinking differently about social issues and how to build community. We believe that new ideas for change come about when people work together to achieve shared goals. We strive to bring together people who would otherwise not get to know each other— there is power in these “learning exchanges.”
facilities.notes: Drop-In hours are from 1:00pm-5:00pm.

facilities.name: Aboriginal Shelter
facilities.welcomes: Male Female Transgender Children Youth Adult Senior
facilities.description: The Aboriginal Shelter is open to all cultures (19 years and older) on a first come, first serve basis. There is space for 100 clients with separated areas for males and females. Doors open at 4:30pm. When signed in, clients receive a blanket and mat and two tickets ( one for an hot dinner meal and one for a sandwich/snack for breakfast in the morning.
facilities.notes:
The Aboriginal Shelter is open to all cultures (19 years and older) on a first come, first serve basis. There is space for 100 clients with separated areas for males and females. Doors open at 4:30pm. When signed in, clients receive a blanket and mat and two tickets: one for an hot dinner meal and one for a sandwich/snack for breakfast in the morning.

Dinner is served between 6:15 and 6:30. Followed by free time to 11pm, at which time, the doors are closed and a bed check is made. Any empty mats are collected and distributed to a wait-list until the facility is full. From this point, there are no in and out privileges. Sandwich and snack are distributed after 8am. Wake call is at 9am and the out time is 10am.

facilities.name: Anchor of Hope
facilities.description: The Anchor Drop-in Centre offers a safe gathering place that provides access to information, resources, and other support services. Visitors to the drop-in centre can enjoy a snack or cup of tea, a board game, colouring, movies, and generally relax and find fellowship with friends new and old.

facilities.name: Covenant House (female shelter)
facilities.description: Covenant House Vancouver exists for those young people for whom there is often no one else - young people who have either willingly fled physical, emotional and/or sexual abuse or those who have been forced from their homes. We understand that life changes are challenging and do everything in our power to ensure that young people succeed at whatever plan they have chosen for themselves. As long as genuine effort is demonstrated, so is our commitment.
facilities.notes: The short-term Residential Crisis Program has 24 beds for female-identified youth.

facilities.name: Covenant House (male shelter)
facilities.description: Covenant House Vancouver exists for those young people for whom there is often no one else - young people who have either willingly fled physical, emotional and/or sexual abuse or those who have been forced from their homes. We understand that life changes are challenging and do everything in our power to ensure that young people succeed at whatever plan they have chosen for themselves. As long as genuine effort is demonstrated, so is our commitment.
facilities.notes: The short-term Residential Crisis Program has 35 beds for male-identified youth.

facilities.name: Belkin House
facilities.description: Belkin House has 2 floors dedicated to hosting a variety of residential programs and 5 floors dedicated to housing up to 225 men, women and children. We are a 24/7 operation and provide a clean, safe, secure and comfortable accommodation for our residents.

facilities.name: Robert and Lily Lee Clinic
facilities.description: Houses the public health unit.

facilities.name: Yukon Shelter
facilities.welcomes: Male Female Transgender Children Youth Adult Senior
facilities.description: The Yukon Shelter is the Lookout Society`s largest and busiest. Built in 2002, it provides 71 beds with 19 dedicated to women. Yukon staff has prioritized individual case planning in an effort to find sustainable housing options for clients and shorten stays at the shelter.
facilities.notes: Small pets are allowed. Wheelchair accessible.

facilities.name: Vi Fineday
facilities.description: Provides 24-hour emergency accommodation for families, single women, single parents (male or female) with their dependent children, and couples without children; 18 beds available in dorm-style bedrooms. Provides three meals and two snacks daily. Small lockers and bus tickets may be available. A case manager helps clients with resources to find housing and employment; clients have access to internet, phones, and a fax.

facilities.name: UGM - The Cornerstone
facilities.description: 365 days a year, hungry men and women can come to Union Gospel Mission for a meal. Each meal is a time to build community, share home-cooked food, and develop connections that can offer a way off the street, out of addiction, and into a brighter future. By serving three nutritious meals a day, we meet our guests’ need for daily bread and offer a connection to UGM’s range of transformative programs and services.

facilities.name: Raincity Triage
facilities.description: The Triage Shelter provides emergency housing and care for people living with mental health, substance use and other challenges. Clients are able to stay longer than at most shelters, which gives shelter staff time to help folks access appropriate support services based on their individuals needs and circumstance. An average length of stay at the shelter can range from 3 days to 6 weeks. Triage is staffed 24 house a day by trained and experienced staff members who liaise with doctors, mental health teams, counselors, and other professionals.

facilities.name: First United Church
facilities.description: First United Church Community Ministry Society operates a low-barrier shelter in the Downtown Eastside of Vancouver, providing 60 beds each night– space for 40 men and 20 women. Shelter residents have 24-access to the building and are provided three meals a day, seven days a week. Shelter residents get 3 meals per day. Friday night dinners and weekend lunches are available to community members.
facilities.notes:
Men must be out of their beds from 9am-7pm unless directed by physician, women can only stay in bed 21 hours out of the day. Rooms are closed for cleaning from 4pm-7pm.

First United Drop-In runs from 8am-5pm, Monday to Friday.

facilities.name: Al Mitchell Place
facilities.description: The Al Mitchell Place Shelter is located in Vancouver`s Downtown Eastside and provides 46 year-round minimum-barrier shelter beds to meet the needs of adult men and women.
facilities.notes: The Al Mitchell Place Shelter is located in Vancouver`s Downtown Eastside and provides 46 year-round minimum-barrier shelter beds to meet the needs of adult men and women.

facilities.name: The Beacon
facilities.description: The Beacon offers 24 hour service to 60 men. Clients are served healthy, nutritious meals, have access to personal hygiene supplies and laundry services, and access to the Vancouver Coastal Health nursing team for health care, a diverse slate of job skills, education, and living skills programming. Clients staying at The Beacon are encouraged to work with our case workers and outreach teams to address their housing obstacles. Staff can assist clients in seeking employment, mental and physical health care, housing, social assistance, and other resources that will help them move from the streets to long-term housing.
facilities.notes: No intakes after 11:30. Closed from 3-4pm for cleaning.

facilities.name: Crosswalk
facilities.description: This shelter offers a low barrier, safe, alcohol- and drug-free overnight shelter for 35 men and women. The Crosswalk is open from 9:30pm to 7:30am nightly. Clients have access to showers and are provided with a snack upon intake and discharge.  Many services are available for referral such as healthcare, lifeskills, outreach and access to caseworkers.
facilities.notes: Open overnight, 9:30pm - 7:30am.

facilities.name: The Haven
facilities.description: The Haven offers 24 hour service to 60 men. Clients are served healthy, nutritious meals, have access to personal hygiene supplies and laundry services, and access to the Vancouver Coastal Health nursing team for health care, a diverse slate of job skills, education, and living skills programming. Clients staying at The Haven are encouraged to work with our case workers and outreach teams to address their housing obstacles. Staff can assist clients in seeking employment, mental and physical health care, housing, social assistance, and other resources that will help them move from the streets to long-term housing.

facilities.name: Powell Place
facilities.description: Powell Place provides emergency shelter for women in crisis while supporting them to foster their independence, enhance their skills, and find and remain in permanent housing. In addition to doubling its occupancy from 26 beds to 52, the new facility allows for integrated community services on site, offering accessible and individualized supports for women in crisis.
facilities.notes: Trans inclusive. Single women and lesbian couples.

facilities.name: Springhouse
facilities.description: Springhouse a women`s shelter. Accepts male children 18 and under. Children and youth receive one-on-one emotional staff support in a child-friendly environment and families are connected with community resources, including schools and clinics. Family-building activities include community kitchens, crafts, games, movie nights, reading circle, group outings and gardening. Parenting support is available to moms, including assistance accessing Ministry of Children and Families Development services.
facilities.notes: Housing and case planning workers are are available full time.

facilities.name: Carrall Street Church
facilities.description: The Gospel Mission is located in the downtown eastside of Vancouver and is the oldest mission in the city and the oldest in Canada. It has been in operation since 1929 and has been at it`s present location since the 1940`s. Offers daily meals or snack at 7:00pm, free showers Monday 7am-9am (ladies only), Tuesday-Friday 6am-10am (co-ed), and Monday and Thursday afternoons from 12pm-2pm.
facilities.notes: Monday hours are 7am-9am, 12pm-2pm, 7pm. Tuesday, Wednesday, and Friday hours are 6am-10am, 7pm. Thursday hours are 6am-10am, 12pm-2pm, 7pm. Closed Saturday and open Sunday for service and meals/snack at 7pm.

facilities.name: YWCA Crabtree Corner
facilities.address: 533 East Hastings Street, Vancouver, BC, V6A 1P9
facilities.description: From transitional housing for expecting and new mothers with substance use issues, to emergency child care, a community kitchen and violence prevention, YWCA Crabtree Corner Community Resource Centre meets women and families where they are at, providing them with the support to move forward in life. Crabtree’s hot meal programs provide breakfast for child care and housing participants and hot lunches on a drop-in basis for women and children in the community. Food is made from scratch using produce from the YWCA’s Rooftop Garden and through generous donations from the community.
facilities.notes: Hot meals served Monday, Tuesday, Thursday and Friday at 3pm. Soup and bannock served on Wednesdays at 12pm.

facilities.name: The Door is Open
facilities.description: The Door Is Open is a drop in centre located at 255 Dunlevy Avenue, in the heart of East Vancouver. The Centre supports the needs of hundreds of people in the downtown east side. Many of our guests have compounding difficulties such as drug and alcohol addiction, physical and mental handicaps as well as maturing life stages and many other impairments.
facilities.notes: Meals served at 11am Monday, Tuesday, Thursday-Saturday. Wednesdays breakfast and lunch for women and children at 8:30am and 11am. Sunday meal served at 12pm. Drop-in open until 3pm.

facilities.name: The Dugout
facilities.description: Over its nearly 45 year history, the Dugout has helped thousands of people through difficult periods of struggle and transformation.  The fact that many of today’s volunteers are yesterday’s patrons pays fitting tribute to the valuable services offered at the Dugout. Each day begins with a nourishing bowl of soup and a warm cup of coffee.  Muffins, cookies, pastries and light meals are available throughout the day along with newspapers, community bulletins, and friendly conversation. The Dugout also serves as an information centre where people can gain access to valuable community resources.  Since 1968 it has hosted the longest running meeting of Alcoholics Anonymous in Vancouver.
facilities.notes: Soup line starts at 7:30am Monday-Saturday, Sunday at 8:30. Drop-in closed from 12:30-1:45 for AA meetings. Pastries, bread, snacks available throughout the day.

facilities.name: Harbour Light Learning Centre
facilities.address: 119 East Cordova Street, Vancouver, BC, V6A 1K8
facilities.description: Harbour Light offers a continuum of care that includes: Daily feeding ministry, Emergency Shelters, Detox Unit, Addiction Stabilization & Treatment Program, Community Residential Facility, Affordable Housing, Volunteer Work Experience Program, Vancouver Community College-Harbour Light Learning Centre, and other educational and skill-building programs, and  more.
facilities.notes: Meal times are Monday and Wednesday and Friday at 11am and 4pm, Tuesday, Saturday, and Sunday at 11am.

facilities.name: Mission Possible
facilities.description: Mission Possible is a non-profit organization in Vancouver, British Columbia providing opportunities for people challenged by homelessness and poverty. In providing street-level assistance like nutrition, clothing, crisis counseling, referrals and spiritual support, we have learned that real transformation and lasting change always happens from the inside out and the bottom up.
facilities.notes: Daily lunch provided for program participants. Community lunch on Saturdays.

facilities.name: Salvation Army Soup Truck
facilities.description: Provides soup and sandwiches on Tuesdays and Sundays.

facilities.name: WISH Drop-In Centre
facilities.description: Operated by women for the exclusive use of female survival sex workers, the WISH Drop-In Centre Society is a registered non-profit society that furnishes a variety of services within a nurturing and non-judgmental environment. In addition to meeting essential needs by serving nutritious, hot meals, providing showering facilities, dispensing make-up, hygiene items, and clothing for up to 120 women each night, WISH offers on-site nursing care, referrals to detox, treatment and shelters. Our programs, including Supported Employment and a Learning Centre, have been successful in providing opportunities for participants to engage in positive, empowering activities in a safe place.
facilities.notes: Meals are served from 6pm-8pm, drop-in is open from 6pm to 12 noon the following day.

facilities.name: Ravensong Community Health Clinic
facilities.description: Ravensong Community Health Centre offers a range of health care services for people of all ages. We provide public and community health services, mental health and addiction services, speech therapy, nutrition counselling, home health services, youth health services and more. The centre works with community organizations and health care providers, such as your family doctor, to keep you and your community healthy. The Primary Care High Needs and Stabilization Clinic at Raven Song supports clients with complex care needs, such as addiction and chronic disease. A health care team of doctors, nurse practitioners, social workers and nurses is available to work with clients to address their health issues.

facilities.name: Three Bridges Clinic
facilities.description: At Three Bridges Community Health Centre you can get your basic health care and learn how to keep yourself healthy. It provides services for people of all ages. The Centre works with community organizations and health care providers, such as your family doctor, to keep people and communities healthy.

facilities.name: Evergreen Community Health Centre
facilities.description: This community health centre provides services for people of all ages and works with community organizations and health care providers, such as your family doctor, to keep people and communities healthy. At Evergreen Community Health Centre we see people who live in Vancouver`s northeast or in Community Health Area 3.

facilities.name: Native Health Clinic
facilities.description: Vancouver Native Health Society (VNHS) was established in 1991 with a mission to improve and promote the physical, mental, emotional and spiritual health of individuals, focusing on the Aboriginal community residing in Greater Vancouver. Today, Vancouver Native Health Society delivers comprehensive medical, counselling and social services generally to Vancouver’s Downtown Eastside Aboriginal community. The majority of our clients struggle with overlapping issues and con-current health issues such as substance abuse, mental health, chronic disease, homelessness and poverty.
facilities.notes: Note: the Clinic stops taking appointments once they are at full capacity.

facilities.name: Pender Community Health Clinic
facilities.description: Pender Community Health Centre provides a many services for people in the Downtown Eastside, Gastown and Strathcona areas. The Centre provides you with health care for present illness and information to prevent future illness. It also offers a full range of addiction and mental health services at this clinic.

facilities.name: Downtown Community Health Clinic
facilities.description: We provide a full range of addiction and mental health services, which are free for those living in the Downtown Eastside and Strathcona area. Clinic services, such as vaccination and primary health care are provided, as well as referral services, support groups and therapy. Our team includes a podiatrist, respiratory therapist, and nutritionist.

facilities.name: 411 Senior`s Center Society
facilities.notes: Social Drop-In runs from 10am-3pm.

facilities.name: AIDS Vancouver Helpline
facilities.description: The AIDS Vancouver Helpline is a confidential and personalized service where we provide the latest HIV related information, referrals and support. Our service is accessible by phone, email or by posting a forum question.

facilities.name: Vancouver Women`s Health Clinic
facilities.description: The VWHC has many different resources related to all aspects of women’s health, including a non-lending library, a practitioner and therapist directory, health files, videos, useful fact sheets (Titbits on things like MSP, Finding a New Doctor, and Patient Rights), along with listings of local support groups and community events. Visit the space to learn more about these services. We offers our services in 9 different languages including:Arabic English, French, Spanish, Cantonese, Thai, Punjabi, Urdu, Farsi, and German.
facilities.notes: These hours are for the VWHC resource centre. Nurse practitioner hours are Monday 9:30am-4:30pm, Tuesday-Thursday 12pm-5pm, and Friday 9am-1:30pm.

facilities.name: CarePoint Medical Centre
facilities.description: Our Physicians Advisory Council establishes and maintains our high standards of medical practice at each clinic, and of our doctors are registered with MSP - the Medical Services Plan of British Columbia.  Below is our current doctor on-call schedule for the coming week.  Please note appointments cannot be made with the on-call doctors, as they are walk-in only.  If you would like to inquire about making an appointment with one of our medical specialists, please contact us.
facilities.notes: Visit their website for a full doctors' schedule. Clinic is open until 8pm but they stop taking appointments at 6:30pm.

facilities.name: Mid-Main Community Health Centre
facilities.description: We are a non-profit society committed to helping you maintain and improve your health. Because good health involves many factors, we provide a range of services in one building that emphasize health education and illness prevention.

facilities.name: Access Pro Bono
facilities.description: Our Mission is to promote access to justice in BC by providing and fostering quality pro bono legal services for people and non-profit organizations of limited means. We also subscribe to a number of supporting Objectives and Principles.
facilities.notes:
Call Access Pro Bono for hours and booking appointments: 604.878.7400 or 1.877.762.6664 (toll-free)
Please note that Access Pro Bono cannot provide legal advice over the telephone or through email.

facilities.name: Law Students' Legal Advice Program
facilities.description: The Law Students’ Legal Advice Program was established in 1969, when students from the UBC Faculty of Law operated a summer legal advice clinic under Vancouver Inner-City Services. This clinic eventually expanded to include a small number of clinics operating on a weekly basis during the school year. In 1978, the program was incorporated as the Greater Vancouver Law Students’ Legal Advice
facilities.notes: Visit the LSLAP website for clinic locations (found under "clinics" tab). Call for information.

facilities.name: Community Legal Assistance Society (CLAS)
facilities.welcomes: Male Female Transgender Children Youth Adult Senior
facilities.description: Through our programs, we deliver legal services in five key areas: housing security, income security, workers rights, human rights and mental health. We focus on these areas because they are tied to fundamental determinants of health. Delivering services in these areas not only has an obvious and immediate benefit to our clients and those impacted by our work, it also reduces public costs associated with the services needed to remedy the significant consequences that arise when these core needs are not met.
facilities.notes: Provides free legal assistance for low-income people, including information and referrals, summary advice, and full representation in regards to reviewing final decisions by administrative bodies including the Residential Tenancy Branch, Employment and Assistance Appeal Tribunal, Employment Standards Branch, Workers' Compensation Appeal Tribunal, Human Rights Tribunal and the Social Security Tribunal. Practice areas also include: human rights cases before the Human Rights Tribunal and representation of people detained under the Mental Health Act or subject to the mental disorder provisions of the Criminal Code.

facilities.name: Downtown Eastside Women`s Center (DEWC)
facilities.notes: Lunch is served daily from 12:30-1:45.

facilities.name: BC Public Interest Advocacy Centre
facilities.description: BC Public Interest Advocacy Centre (BCPIAC) is a not-for-profit law office based in Vancouver, coast Salish Territories. Our mission is to advance the interests of groups that are generally unrepresented or underrepresented in issues of major public concern. We do this through two areas of work:  representing low and fixed income people of British Columbia in matters that relate to utility regulation;  and, strategic anti-poverty and  social justice issues before  courts and tribunals in BC.

facilities.name: Positive Women`s Network
facilities.description: Positive Women’s Network provide leadership, support and education on HIV-related health, social and prevention initiatives for women.

facilities.name: Atira Women`s Resource Society
facilities.description: Free legal advocacy services for women in the Downtown Eastside. Atira`s legal advocate provides information, support and assistance in the following areas of law: Family law, Ministry of Children and Families (MCFD), minor criminal law issues (including victims of crime), Aboriginal law issues, Police Complaints, Ombudsperson Complaints, Small Claims issues, Freedom of Information Requests. Atira`s legal advocate also provides information, advice and full representation services (including up to Tribunal level) in the following areas:  Welfare, Disability, CPP, Employment Insurance, Worksafe (WCB), Tenancy, Crime Victim Assistance Program appeals, and Human Rights.
facilities.notes: Because Atira has only one full-time legal advocate, it is unlikely that unscheduled appointments can be accommodated. For an appointment please call or email legaladvocate@atira.bc.ca. Your message will be answered as soon as possible. Given the current demands on the legal advocacy program there may be a 1-3 week wait to make an appointment.

facilities.name: Community of Hope
facilities.description: Serves snacks and coffee at 12 noon and lunch from 1:15 pm to 2 pm Tuesday to Saturday. Closed during welfare week each month.
facilities.notes: Serves snacks and coffee at 12 noon and lunch from 1:15 pm to 2 pm Tuesday to Saturday. Closed during welfare week each month.

facilities.name: Food on the Corner Society
facilities.description: Volunteers provide hot soup, sandwiches, sweets, and coffee from 11am to 1pm on Saturdays.

facilities.name: Evelyne Saller Centre (The 44)
facilities.description: The Evelyne Saller Centre provides a variety of services to low income and at risk adults living in the Downtown Eastside. The centre supports the physical, mental, and social well-being of community members to enhance their quality of life. Facilities at the Evelyne Saller Centre include a low-cost cafeteria, free showers and laundry service, and a variety of recreational programs both within and outside the centre.
facilities.notes: Cafeteria is open from 10am-2:50pm and from 3:30pm to 5:50pm. Showers are available on Saturday and Sunday from 10am-12:30pm and 2pm-4:30pm, Monday from 9:15am to 3:30pm, and Tuesday-Friday from 9:15am-7:30pm. Laundry is available Monday to Friday after 9am. Delousing is by appointment only from Tuesday to Friday.

facilities.name: Kiwassa Neighbourhood House
facilities.description: Kiwassa Food Programs provide the tools and knowledge to increase food security in our neighbourhood and to build healthier lifestyles, families, and eating habits. Kiwassa’s food programs include free or very low cost snacks and meals, a family food bank, canning workshops, cooking classes, and community gardens.
facilities.notes: Kiwassa runs a variety of food programs for all ages. Breakfast program for children and families runs from 8am-8:45am. Coffee is offered daily from 8am-2pm. Children and Youth who are a part of some of Kiwassa`s afterschool programs are also offered snacks and meals. Seniors lunch is a three course multicultural lunch offered every Friday at noon.

facilities.name: Living Waters Mission
facilities.description: A  meal of hotdogs, coleslaw and juice is served at the end of every service, and special dinners are served on Holidays.

facilities.name: Downtown Eastside Women`s Center Emergency Shelter
facilities.notes: Hot Tea is served until 2am. Provides feminine hygiene products.

facilities.name: Reach Community Health Centre
facilities.description: REACH Community Health Centre is celebrating its 45th year. Our interdisciplinary team offers a variety of health and social services under one roof, which means we strive to be much more than just a doctor’s or dentist’s office. Services we provide include: primary health care within a team setting, groups and health education, dental services, pharmacy, counseling, social work services, and the Multicultural Family Centre. Our dental clinic and pharmacy are open to the  Other programs have some admissions criteria or have a program focus.
facilities.notes: Clinic is by appointment only. Reach offers "advanced access" to appointments, offering services in a timely manner. The goal is to help avoid emergency room visits. Call the clinic to make an appointment. Youth drop-in clinic operates Wednesday evenings from 5-7:30pm.

facilities.name: St. Mary`s Kerrisdale Community Meal
facilities.description: Provides lunch every Tuesday afternoon.
facilities.notes: Over the summer, St. Mary`s will be providing bagged lunches on Tuesdays from 11:30am-12pm. The hot lunch program resumes on Tuesday, September 15, 2015.

facilities.name: Dr. Peter Centre
facilities.description:
The Dr. Peter AIDS Foundation is a non-profit organization that raises funds to support innovative health care at the Dr. Peter Centre in Metro Vancouver. The Dr. Peter Centre is British Columbia’s only HIV/AIDS Day Health Program and 24-hour nursing care Residence.
The only program of its kind in Canada, the Dr. Peter Centre is a leader in HIV care, particularly for individuals with multiple medical conditions and social barriers.

facilities.name: John Ruedy Immunodeficiency Clinic
facilities.description:
The John Ruedy Immunodeficiency Clinic (IDC) at St. Paul’s Hospital is a collaboration between the BC-CfE and Providence Health Care (PHC). The IDC brings together an interdisciplinary team of family doctors, specialists, nurses, pharmacists, counsellors, social workers, and nutritionists to provide a broad range of primary care and support services for HIV-positive patients.

For information and appointments, call (604) 806-8060, our direct nurse line (604) 806-9303, or the direct POC line (604) 561-4896. You do not need a referral to visit the IDC. The clinic hours are 8am-8pm Monday through Thursday, and 8am-4pm on Fridays. For POC HIV Testing, we only take appointments up until 3:30pm through the weekdays, and provide after-hours medical support through an on-call physician
facilities.notes: For information and appointments, call (604) 806-8060, our direct nurse line (604) 806-9303, or the direct POC line (604) 561-4896. You do not need a referral to visit the IDC. facilities.description: The Advocacy Office provides free information and support to persons needing access to social services. Clients bring various needs, ranging from welfare applications, crisis grant application, health care issues, short- and long-term housing problems, legal aid, and more.

facilities.notes:
Wednesdays, 6:00-9:00pm is the free drop-in night of skill-sharing, problem-solving, and education.If you have computer/tech issues they will assist.

Entry via back door. Bike parking located in the front. Unfortunately the location is currently not wheelchair accessible. No pre-registration required; first-come, first-served.

facilities.name: Gastown Vocational Services
